observations.recommendation:
We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor to:
Re-organize the Inventory Committee in a memorandum or  Executive Order as necessary,  responsible for the conduct of a thorough and complete physical count of all properties at least once a year and subsequently prepare the RPCPPE using the proper format and to submit a copy of the said reports to the Audit Team not later than January 31 of every year;  The committee may have same composition with ispection committee of the LGU but with technical knowhow in the conduct of physical count, property ledger cards and property cards.
Update the job description of the Property Officer to include maintaining Property Cards for all the PPEs of the LGU;
Municipal Accountant to maintain  Property Ledger Cards and be reconciled with the Property Cards of the Property Officer;
Direct the Property Officer, the Inventory Committee and the Municipal Accountant to adhere with the guidelines and procedures set forth under COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020, to reflect reliable balances of PPE accounts.
Furthermore, we have recommended that all issued property and equipment with a unit cost below the capitalization threshold of P50,000.00, that are still included in the PPE accounts, be appropriately derecognized from the PPE accounts pursuant to COA Circular No. 2022-004, dated May 31, 2022, and COA Circular No. 2024-006, dated March 14, 2024.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor instruct the:
Municipal Accountant to:
Conduct analysis and review the cause of discrepancy by tracing and locating the documents affecting the reciprocal accounts;
Prepare the necessary adjusting entries in the books of accounts through the preparation of a Journal Entry Voucher (JEV), duly supported with documents, explanations, and/or computations to reflect the correct balances of accounts in the financial statements;
Maintain subsidiary ledger and conduct regular reconciliation of the accounts to ensure that the balances of reciprocal accounts are the same at all times;
Communicate with the Municipal Engineer to identify the discrepancy of the balance presented in the Construction in Progress Accounts and the year-end Reports on Government Projects, Programs, and Activities Report:
Municipal Engineer:
To provide a timely copy of the Quarterly Projects, Programs, and Activities Reports to the Municipal Accountant, stamped as received, and indicate the date of receipt.

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant, Municipal Treasurer, and the concerned municipal employee to:
Observe the timely remittance of tax dues/withheld from employees/suppliers, premium contributions of both employer and employee, as well as the loan repayments to the concerned Offices, as the case may be, as prescribed by BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth to avoid possible penalties;
Remit all taxes withheld, premium contributions, and loan repayment intact on or before the deadline as provided in the rules and regulations set by the BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth to avoid penalties, surcharges, and interests from delayed remittances;
Reconcile the Due to BIR, GSIS, PAG-IBIG, and PhilHealth accounts with the actual amounts withheld based on the filed tax returns, statement of account, and loan amortization schedule from respective agencies, to identify the under- and over-remittances incurred from prior years until the current year; and
Encourage all employees to download and use GSIS, PAGIBIG, and Philhealth apps in mobile devices to monitor personal contributions, claims, and loan payments.

Formulate policies and guidelines or adopt the policies and guidelines promulgated by DSWD on the grant of financial assistance under the AICS program to strengthen the controls employed in the selection of eligible beneficiaries;

Formalize these policies through the issuance of Executive Order, memorandum or equivalent document which will serve as a source of guidance in the implementation of AICs; and

Ensure that the MSWDO strictly assess and evaluate all applicants requesting financial assistance out of the AICS program including the identification of nearest kin who serves as the claimant.

Coordinate with the Municipal Disaster Risk and Reduction Management Officer to determine the final amount of unexpended balance to be transferred to the Special Trust Fund;

Ensure timely recording and recognition of the transfer of the unexpended balance of the QRF and the DRRMF-MOOE of DRMMF to the Special Trust Fund under the account "Trust Liability-DRRM" in the Trust Fund Books at year-end, in accordance with Item 5.1.10 of COA Circular No. 2012-002;

Provide the details of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF as supplementary disclosures in the Note to Financial Statements, as required by Item 5.1.16 of COA Circular 2012-002; and

We have recommended that the Municipal Mayor instructs the Municipal Treasurer to (a) prepare a letter along with the inventory of obsolete, spoiled, and cancelled accountable forms, including the checks found during the cash examination, requesting inspection and destruction thereof and submit the same to the Audit Team; 

(b) maintain an inventory list of all obsolete, spoiled and cancelled accountable forms, in addition to the RAAF, to help the Management monitor such accountable forms subject for inspection and destruction by the Audit Team pursuant to Section 99 of GAAM, Volume I; and 



(c) inform all accountable officers to mark cancelled accountable forms, including checks, with the word “Cancelled” noted by the Municipal Treasurer or her duly authorized representative for an effective internal control over cancellation of accountable forms.

We recommended the Management to:


Instruct the Municipal Accountant to record accounts of the municipality diligently to avoid discrepancies in the financial books;

Submit the documentary requirements required under item 5.7.1 of COA Circular 2012-001 for the payment of the aforementioned honoraria to personnel involved in procurement together with the complete list of successfully awarded procurement contracts entered into through competitive public bidding and records of collections from successfully completed procurement projects such as the proceeds from the sale of bidding documents per Item 3.0 of DBM Budget Circular No. 2007-3;

Submit authority from the Sanggunian, if any, for the BAC to use savings from the General Fund for 2020 for the payment of their honoraria as required under item 3.1.4 of DBM Budget Circular No. 2007-3; and

Pay only claims that are supported with a sufficient budget in order to establish the validity of the transaction.

We have recommended that the management strictly monitor the liquidation of cash advances. It is further recommended that:

No additional cash advance be given to officials/employees unless the previous cash advances was settled and the liquidating papers were submitted to the auditor for post-audit;

Exert all possible remedies to collect and demand liquidation of cash advances;

The Municipal Accountant should discourage the partial liquidation per cash advance voucher. The balance shall be strictly refunded upon liquidation; and

Require the Municipal Accountant see to it that supporting documents are complete before certifying the Disbursement Voucher and granting payment of cash advances.

